(532, 'Publish', NULL, '2015-07-23 14:39:39', 'Mammals', 'Other', '313', 'Mammalia', 'Tubulidentata', 'Orycteropodidae', 'Orycteropus afer', '', 'Aardvark', '88.83410502', 'LC', '4.49796469', 'Aardvarks are considered a keystone species by some biologists because so many other animals are heavily reliant on their burrows for shelter.', 'The name aardvark comes from the Africaan/Dutch meaning "earth pig". This name is very fitting as the aardvark resembles a medium to large size pig and is an accomplished burrower. Aardvarks are considered a keystone species by some biologists because so many other animals are heavily reliant on their burrows for shelter.', 'Aardvark, Antbear', '', 'N', 'N', '', '', ''),
(533, 'Publish', NULL, '2014-01-25 18:12:45', 'Mammals', 'Other', '318', 'Mammalia', 'Monotremata', 'Ornithorhynchidae', 'Ornithorhynchus anatinus', '', 'Platypus', '86.73092369', 'LC', '4.47427444', 'The duck-billed platypus is the most evolutionary distinct mammal alive today.', 'The notion of the duck-billed platypus possessing a bird like horny bill originated from examinations of dried specimens. The bill is actually soft, moist and leathery and also highly sensitive. The duck-billed platypus is the most evolutionary distinct mammal alive today.', 'Platypus, Duck-billed Platypus', '', 'N', 'N', '', '', ''),
(534, 'Publish', NULL, NULL, 'Mammals', 'Other', '580', 'Mammalia', 'Monotremata', 'Tachyglossidae', 'Tachyglossus aculeatus', '', 'Short-beaked Echidna', '55.87995761', 'LC', '4.04094304', 'The name echidna orginates from the Greek goodess Ekhidna who was believed to be half reptile and half mammal, with the face of a woman but the body of a serpent.', 'The name echidna orginates from the Greek goodess Ekhidna who was believed to be half reptile and half mammal, with the face of a woman but the body of a serpent. Echidnas are monotremes. Monotremes differ from all other mammals and resemble reptiles in that they lay shell covered eggs that hatch outside the mother''s body.', 'Short-beaked Echidna, Kangaroo Island Echidna', '', 'N', 'N', '', '', ''),
(535, 'Publish', NULL, NULL, 'Mammals', 'Other', '603', 'Mammalia', 'Pilosa', 'Cyclopedidae', 'Cyclopes didactylus', '', 'Pygmy Anteater', '53.97275685', 'LC', '4.00683773', 'The silky anteater is the world''s smallest anteater species and is little bigger than a human hand. It is rarely seen due to its small size and its nocturnal (or night-active) and arboreal lifestyle.', 'The silky anteater is the world''s smallest anteater species and is little bigger than a human hand. It is rarely seen due to its small size and its nocturnal (or night-active) and arboreal lifestyle, and it is even seldom encountered by forest tribes. It has a prehensile tail and long claws for climbing and tearing open ant''s nests.', 'Pygmy Anteater, Silky Anteater', '', 'N', 'N', '', '', ''),
(536, 'Publish', NULL, NULL, 'Mammals', 'Other', '923', 'Mammalia', 'Rodentia', 'Pedetidae', 'Pedetes capensis', '', 'Spring Hare', '34.22627950', 'LC', '3.56179238', 'The spring hare is the only species within the only genus of the family Pedetidae, there are two distinct subpopulations. It has an uncertain lineage.', 'The spring hare is the only species within the only genus of the family Pedetidae, there are two distinct subpopulations. \rIt has an uncertain lineage and has previously been classified with both porcupines (Hystricomydae) and the family of rodents including squirrels, parie dogs and chipmunks (Sciuridae).', 'Spring Hare, Springhaas, Springhare', '', 'N', 'N', '', '', ''),
