(1942, 'Publish', '2014-02-20 16:23:11', '2014-02-20 16:23:11', 'Birds', 'EDGE', '94', 'Aves', 'Passeriformes', 'Sylviidae (or Macrosphenidae)', 'Macrosphenus pulitzeri', NULL, 'Pulitzer''s Longbill', '15.832729\r\n', 'EN', '4.902767\r\n', 'Shy by nature, this longbill has been difficult to study and very little is known about its ecology or population size.', 'This endangered longbill is found only in west Angola. A shy species, this bird has been the subject of few research projects and very little is known about its ecology, breeding habits or tolerance of degraded habitats.', 'Pulitzer’s Greenbul, Pulitzer''s Bush-Creeper', 'None', 'N', '', 'Angola', NULL, NULL),
(1943, 'Publish', '2014-02-20 16:23:11', '2014-04-23 16:25:52', 'Birds', 'EDGE', '40', 'Aves', 'Passeriformes', 'Colluricinclidae', 'Colluricincla sanghirensis', 'Colluricincla megarhyncha sanghirensis, Coracornis sanghirensis, Dendrocincla macrorhyncha,Pinarolestes sanghirensis', 'Sangihe Shrike-thrush', '11.944888\r\n', 'CR', '5.33329\r\n', 'With numbers thought be as low as 100 individuals, the Sangihe shrike-thrush could be on the verge of extinction.', 'With its restricted range, small population and dependence on primary forest, the Sangihe shrike-thrush is on the verge of extinction. Only urgent and effective protection of remaining forest tracts can ensure the survival of this species.', 'Sangihe Shrikethrush, Sahengbalira Shrike-thrush, Large Tyrannine Woodcreeper', 'Limited', 'N', 'N', 'Indonesia', NULL, NULL),
(1944, 'Publish', '2014-02-20 16:51:37', '2015-05-14 17:23:07', 'Birds', 'EDGE', '15', 'Aves', 'Podicipediformes', 'Podicipedidae', 'Podiceps gallardoi', NULL, 'Hooded Grebe', '16.908686\r\n', 'CR', '5.657875\r\n', 'The critically endangered hooded grebe was first discovered in 1974.', 'The hooded grebe is an attractive bird that inhabits basaltic lakes in South America. It is thought that the population has declined by more than 80% in the past 26 years. The current population is estimated to stand at around 800 mature individuals.', NULL, 'Active', 'N', 'N', 'Argentina; Chile', NULL, NULL),
(1945, 'Publish', '2014-03-27 10:19:18', '2014-03-27 10:19:18', 'Birds', 'EDGE', '2', 'Aves', 'Aegotheliformes', 'Aegothelidae', 'Aegotheles savesi', NULL, 'New Caledonian Owlet-nightjar', '40.260826\r\n', 'CR', '6.492502\r\n', 'With only two known specimens and a small number of sightings, little is known about this enigmatic species.', 'This enigmatic species has not been seen since 1998, when it was seen chasing insects in the canopy at dusk, and has been presumed extinct by several authorities. Very little is known about the bird and this lack of knowledge needs to be addressed before conservation measures can be put in place.', 'Enigmatic owlet-nightjar, New Caledonian Owlet-Nightjar', 'None', 'Y', '', 'New Caledonia', NULL, NULL),
(1946, 'Publish', '2014-03-27 10:21:18', '2014-03-27 10:21:18', 'Birds', 'EDGE', '4', 'Aves', 'Psittaciformes', 'Psittacidae', 'Strigops habroptila', 'Strigops habroptilus', 'Kakapo', '32.371539\r\n', 'CR', '6.280292\r\n', 'Found only in New Zealand, this charismatic, flightless parrot is slowly being brought back from the edge of extinction.', 'This beautiful, large parrot is unique in being the only flightless parrot and the only parrot with a lek mating system. Unfortunately, the arrival of humans and introduced mammals has brought it almost to the point of extinction. Through dedicated conservation efforts, numbers are slowly increasing.', 'Owl parrot', 'Active', 'N', '', 'New Zealand', NULL, NULL),
(1947, 'Publish', '2014-03-27 10:25:40', '2014-04-07 14:01:31', 'Birds', 'EDGE', '5', 'Aves', 'Gruiformes', 'Rhynochetidae', 'Rhynochetos jubatus', 'Rhinochetus jubatus', 'Kagu', '55.381864\r\n', 'EN', '6.111589\r\n', 'This ash-white bird is mainly found in the dense, humid forests of New Caledonia and is known locally as the ‘ghost of the forest’.', 'Known by locals as the ‘ghost of the forest’ this highly unusual bird is found on one island in New Caledonia. The only representative of an entire avian family, the Kagu has several unique features, which no other bird possesses.', NULL, 'Active', 'N', '', 'New Caledonia', NULL, NULL),
(1948, 'Publish', '2014-03-27 10:25:40', '2014-04-22 15:40:53', 'Birds', 'EDGE', '8', 'Aves', 'Falconiformes (or Accipitriformes)', 'Accipitridae', 'Pithecophaga jefferyi', NULL, 'Philippine Eagle', '23.637324\r\n', 'CR', '5.976851\r\n', 'One of the largest and rarest eagles on the planet, this incredible predator has a truly unique evolutionary history.', 'With its large blue eyes and lion’s mane crest, this intimidating eagle is one of the biggest raptors in the world. Despite being the national symbol of the Philippines, the species is on the edge of extinction, primarily due to hunting and habitat loss.', 'Great Philippine Eagle, Monkey-eating Eagle, Banog, Haribon, Haring ibon, Agila', 'Active', 'N', '', 'Philippines', NULL, NULL),
(1949, 'Publish', '2014-03-27 10:31:43', '2015-04-02 17:38:55', 'Birds', 'EDGE', '39', 'Aves', 'Ciconiiformes', 'Threskiornithidae', 'Nipponia nippon', NULL, 'Asian Crested Ibis', '25.031192\r\n', 'EN', '5.338737\r\n', 'This beautiful rose-tinted ibis, like many of its relatives, was once hunted for its unique feathers.', 'This striking, rose-coloured ibis is highly distinctive. Unfortunately, its beauty and medical uses contributed towards its decline as it was hunted for its unique plumage and corpse. Captive-breeding and protection of habitat, means numbers are now on the increase.', 'Toki, Asian Crested Ibis, Crested Ibis, Japanese Crested Ibis, Oriental Crested Ibis, Oriental Ibis, Japanese White Ibis', 'Active', 'N', '', 'China; Russian Federation', NULL, NULL),
(1950, 'Publish', '2014-03-27 10:31:43', '2015-07-23 15:03:33', 'Birds', 'EDGE', '20', 'Aves', 'Ciconiiformes', 'Threskiornithidae', 'Bostrychia bocagei', 'Bostrichia bocagei, Bostrychia olivacea bocagei, Bostrychia olivacea bocagei/rothschildi, Lampribis olivacea bocagei', 'Dwarf Olive Ibis', '14.712093\r\n', 'CR', '5.527019\r\n', 'This small forest ibis is endemic to the island of São Tomé.', 'This endemic forest bird is declining due to habitat destruction, disturbance and hunting pressure. The ecology of the species is not fully understood but research is currently being carried out to improve this. The population is currently thought to be in decline.', 'São Tomé Ibis', 'Limited', 'N', '', 'Sao Tome and Principe', NULL, NULL),
