(1968, 'Publish', '2014-03-27 11:01:27', '2014-04-16 16:24:50', 'Birds', 'EDGE', '28', 'Aves', 'Falconiformes (or Accipitriformes)', 'Accipitridae', 'Sagittarius serpentarius', 'Sagittarius serpentarius gambiensis', 'Secretarybird', '59.325062\r\n', 'VU', '5.486042\r\n', 'With its unmistakable appearance, this long-legged bird of prey is one of Africa’s most iconic species.', 'This tall, long-legged predator stalks the savanna and grasslands of Africa hunting for food. When it finds its prey, it stamps on it until it is dead. Classified as Vulnerable, this species still numbers in the thousands, but is experiencing a rapid decline in population size.', 'Longed-Legged Marching Eagle, Secretary Falcon, Secretary Vulture.', 'None', 'N', '', 'Angola; Benin; Botswana; Burkina Faso; Burundi; Cameroon; Central African Republic; Chad; Congo, The Democratic Republic of the; Cote d''Ivoire; Djibouti; Eritrea; Ethiopia; Gambia; Ghana; Guinea-Bissau; Kenya; Lesotho; Malawi; Mali; Mauritania; Mozambique; Namibia; Niger; Nigeria; Senegal; Somalia; South Africa; South Sudan; Sudan; Swaziland; Tanzania, United Republic of; Togo; Uganda; Zambia; Zimbabwe', NULL, NULL),
(1971, 'Publish', '2014-03-27 11:02:29', '2014-03-27 11:02:29', 'Birds', 'EDGE', '75', 'Aves', 'Passeriformes', 'Dasyornithidae', 'Dasyornis brachypterus', 'Dasyornis brachypterus brachypterus', 'Eastern Bristlebird', '18.16695\r\n', 'EN', '5.032629\r\n', 'The Eastern Bristlebird is found only in eastern Australia. A terrestrial bird, it is particularly vulnerable to wildfires.', 'There are two subspecies of Eastern Bristlebird, both of which are found in Australia. With a total population size of about 2,550 adults, the species is endangered. Due to its reliance on dense understory vegetation left unburnt for five years or more, wildfires are a particular threat to the species.', 'Bristle Bird, Brown Bristlebird, Common Bristlebird', 'Active', 'N', 'N', 'Australia', NULL, NULL);
